title: FT-5 CANOPY FRAME AND SPOOL MOUNT

description.text:
A canopy , or roof system , for Folgertech FT-5 3D Printer. My main purpose for the design was to get rid of the cable chains and have a place for the wire loom to drop in from around center. Also, was hoping to have an easier time fully enclosing the machine to run ABS. Then I created the arm brackets which turned into multi purpose spool holders. The spool holder brackets can be used in a number of ways. You can just drop in a 5/16 threaded rod across them. You can add 608 bearing to the threaded rod and press them into the cutouts. You can just hang the spool directly from the arms. In a few pics attached I used Ramons universal spool holders on the 5/16 threaded rod.

You do not need to print with any supports. You do need a few items though.

BOM
24 - 5mm x 10mm screws
24 - 5mm Twist N Lock nuts
4 - 9" long pieces of 2020 extrusion
2 - 5" long pieces of 2020 extrusion
2 - 6.875" long pieces of 2020 extrusion

Spool Rod
1- 16" long 5/16-18 threaded rod
2 - 5/16 - 18 nylock nuts
2 - 608 bearings (drop into the spool holders recess)

All my files come in rotated but I assure you nothing needs supports if you have decent cooling. The 2020 does fit relatively tight but I had them a bit too loose on the first go around so you may to press in the connections.

When you assemble, create the top rectangle first and fit the lid over the extrusions so you have the spacing exactly right. Then add the angled 2020 and attach to top of machine.

If you like the dlink camera mounts I use the one I designed is here for 2020 extrusion and works excellent for the FT-5 https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2440785

Overview
Printable chain was designed for easy printing and quick assembly, but also to be integrated into any project that needs a drive chain. Printable chain is surprisingly strong, withstanding 20 lbs of pull force before breaking, yet fast and easy to print. All that is needed is 3mm or 1.75mm filament to act as the pin, and a round file in case the holes turn out a little misshapen.

Printing
Printing the chain is pretty straight forward. I slowed my speeds by about 25% and first layer speeds by 50%. Printing at 200 microns, the chain may not look as good, but is mechanical sound and much faster. Printing at 100 microns required a 250% first layer height for the print to stick. Printed the chain with abs @ 245c on 100c pei.

Testing
While testing the strength of the chain, I was able to safely suspend a 15 lb weight with 1 strand of chain without any bending or cracking. Pulling 20 lbs with 1 strand after about 5 seconds resulted in failure. Safe working load is around 10~15 lbs with 1 strand of chain. Hooking the chain into a loop resulted in more strength, breaking at 40 LBS. Safe load with loop of chain being around 20~30 lbs. Surprisingly, the 1.75mm chain held up better in terms of strength, but not as smooth.

Sprockets
I have designed the sprockets to be a universal fit for most small motors with shafts ranging from ~3-8mm. The sprockets use M3 screws and nuts. Simply glue the nut in place and drill out center hole to fit your motor shaft. The sprockets print to fit a 3mm shaft but can be drilled larger. If drilling is required, set your slicer to 5 or more outline shells so no infill is exposed. The sprockets are 10, 15 and 20 tooth but I will be uploading more sizes.

Any suggestions are welcome. Happy printing

The tolerances on the chain are tight, but most printers should be able to print just fine. Cut filament into ~15mm pieces. The width of the chain is 14mm but a little extra does not hurt. A file may be needed to make the holes round, but the inner hole should not need much. The filament needs to fit snugly into the inner hole, but move freely in the outer holes. If the filament happens to come out, a little glue in the inner hole should do the trick.

Better late than never. I was in the process of making this several months ago before a long road of having to move all my things into a small apartment where I can't use my printer, and in being hospitalized.

This is an attempt at Milton Wood's patent for a differential motion spacing bearing, which uses rollers to separate its rollers. It is designed for radial load capacity only, and judging by how it feels, I think it can hold quite a lot of weight!

I made this because of its similarity to Daniel Christiansen's bearing. Many people believe Christiansen's invention is identical, but I demonstrate otherwise. There are a number of key differences. One, in my case, is that this one was actually more difficult to design.

It's not the best. There is definitely a degree of slipping. I assume that is on my error, but I haven't ever seen another working replica of this invention yet. Every so number of turns, the slippage brings some of the rollers closer and closer until a pop is heard and symmetry is gained again momentarily... Terrible! It took many attempts at different roller diameter ratios in order to get something that barely worked. Even so I do think it has quite the strenuous radial load capacity, and if overloaded, will transfer the force into friction rather than seize.

description.text:
This cat toy rolls and wobbles erratically, and is full of catnip!

It is unsymmetrical, and the shorter end is almost solid to add weight and balance the toy so it will roll. As it rolls, any sideways wobble changes the diameter of the "wheel", so it rolls, turns and wobbles in a chaotic manner.

The catnip is added by pausing the print, so the catnip is trapped inside. Print it with the perforated end down, and pause at a Z height of about 55mm. Add the catnip, using a funnel if necessary, and tamp it down gently before resuming the print.

Use dried catnip which has been lightly moistened. This is for two reasons: to keep the catnip from being blown around by the extruder fan, and to keep the catnip from being baked too dry over the heated bed, Before starting the print, spread your dried catnip on a piece of scrap paper, and lightly spritz with clean water using a spray bottle. Don't get it soggy, just lightly damp. I didn't measure the catnip, but I think I used about a heaping tablespoon or so for each toy.

Remove the print promptly so the catnip does not dry out too much in the heated environment of your 3D printing area.

Print with any rigid material which can render the 1mm holes. I used PET-G for mine (specifically, nGen and colorFabb-HT) but PLA would also be a good choice. (A material with a stronger odor, like ABS, might not be to your cat's liking.) Use your standard print settings for your material. To make it balance properly, try an infill of about 75%.

description.text:
I wanted to design a fun flyer. Something small that I could fly around the local parks and was durable. My other goal was to make it easy to 3D print. What I came up with is lack-lusterly called DroneOne. The frame was designed around the Tattu 2S 450mAh battery (SKU: A-75C-450-2S1P-L-XT30), to use 2" props, and 1103 motors (though upgrading the frame for 1104-1106 would be trivial). Highly recommend printing in Taulman 910 filament as it is MUCH more durable than my previous prints in ABS. I can print all the parts for this drone in about 2 hours (printing the main frame in one print, then the motor mounts and camera mount in another). The camera mount ended up a bit soft, so I usually just wrap a rubber band around it for added strength. All in all it is a fun flyer that can bounce off trees and keep on flying!

description.text:
This will allow you to mount an aftermarket 80mm x 10mm 24v/2pin cooling fan to the Monoprice Maker Ultimate printer extruder. Also includes multiple 80mm duct types.

The dimensions account completely for the height of the stock shroud, so the overall clearance will be exactly the same, meaning the stock screws for the 40mm fan will work just fine. You will however, need your own mounting screws for the 80mm fan, which need a properly sized nut/bolt to properly mount it.

It also includes a special slot for the spacers that come with the stock cooler fan, making it easier to reattach everything. You just drop the spacers into the little hole at the top, align it, and screw everything it.

Includes spacers for the 80mm screws to offset the height of the 40mm screw heads. I've also included a very basic simpler version that foregoes the 40mm slots and risers, and allows for more space if one needs it.

Print solid for strength and thermal load so that nothing droops when things heat up. This part will reduce your print area size.

description.text:
Fidget Cube!

Remix of Fidget Cube by surferboy. Printed with high infill, 8% triangular supports everywhere, and a skirt. A 0.2 mm layer will give you a rough texture and a 0.15 layer will be a bit smoother. Printed with PLA but ABS is also an option. Shake polish or light sanding can also be done before assembly.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select V2.1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.15 or 0.2 mm

Infill:

100%

Step 1

Print and remove all supports completely. A pair of flat pliers with a twist seemed to work the best. Then a razor knife to remove all the extra bits if necessary. Make sure the indention for the spinner is completely clear of any support material for smooth operation.

On the spinner side remove the bits toward the top of the cube for free spins. Step 2 - Parts List

Per cube order:

McMaster:

1 x Ball Bearings: https://www.mcmaster.com/#9292k49/=18jnee0 $4.16
1 x Screws: https://www.mcmaster.com/#91290a017/=18jneph $11.00 (can use any M2 from 5 - 10 mm however) ((also, a 1.5 mm hex key is needed))

Sparkfun:
5 x https://www.sparkfun.com/products/97 $1.75
2 x https://www.sparkfun.com/products/8837 $1.90 (or use 1 momentary and 1 toggle, they need to be in this form factor however)
1 x https://www.sparkfun.com/products/9426 $3.50

  • ~$12 shipping

Approximately $7.68 in hardware cost per cube

These items would be great to add on to an existing order. Also, a small breadboard cutout is needed for secure fastening of the push buttons. This part should be 26 x 22 mm and have sanded edges.

Step 3 - Breadboard

After cutting and sanding the breadboard, insert it in through the toggle switch opening at an angle. It was easier to insert as shown below due to the extra material needed for the spinner. Test fit the board in place. One the fit is snug inside the frame, remove and place some dots of super glue where they will not be seen. Reinstall and press firmly. Second image below is fully installed board.

Step 4 - PBs

Bend the legs of the PBs straight then slightly inward to align with the holes in the breadboard. The center PB legs need to be bent in more as the holes are not centered. (fixable mistake in the CAD model but meh it works)

After the pins are flattened, it seems easier to move the pliers away from the body of the PB slightly. Then, press the pliers in toward the center of the PB. A "kink" is formed and the legs are still perpendicular to the body of the PB.

Step 5 - Solder in PBs

Solder each leg of the PBs onto the breadboard for structural integrity. Be careful here as the iron tip or shaft will melt the plastic!

Step 6 - Toggle

Twist off the toggle switch pins for fitment. Insert the slide joystick into the toggle switch hole. align with the opening of the joystick. Press in 1 of the toggle switches then the other. Super glue can be used to hold the joystick in place but is unnecessary.

Step 7 - Ball Bearing

Press in the ball bearing. It should fit and spin with ease. If the ball is pressed too hard however, it can be dislocated.

title: Spider Robot wide body for Nano expansion board
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Modified body of Regis Hsu's Spider Robot to accommodate the Arduino Nano with expansion board and the DC-DC voltage converter.

The Nano expansion board eliminates the need for customized PCB. It has all the pin headers for connecting the servos and the Bluetooth module which make the wiring very convenient. Minimum soldering is needed. However the Nano expansion board won't be able to provide enough current for the servos, an additional DC-DC converter is used and wired to the 5V bus on the expansion board to power the entire system. I used two 18650 Li-on batteries and a LM2596 DC-DC module.

The set up is 100% compatible with the Regis Hsu's original code (remember to change the baud rate to 9600 for the Bluetooth connection).

I bought all the parts online, the total part cost is less than $30 USD and will take 2-4 hours to assemble. Have fun!

See it in action: https://youtu.be/sgeVZeRa-TA

description.text:
Update June 08, 2012:
I've created a version 2 of the double battery cover that is designed to look better, enjoy! Update June 06, 2012:
After a little experimentation, I found it is easier to assemble if your batteries are facing negative side up, and the button feels better if you clip the top LED lead short enough that it just crosses the center of wedge on the underside of the button. I'm always a fan of having handy flashlights on my keys, I find plenty of uses for them. I've taken Roland's motorcycle keychain and modified it so it can house an LED light! The only things you need, other than printing the plastic parts, are an LED, a small plastic tube, and one or two batteries of either CR2032 or CR2016.

Materials:
  • One 5mm diameter LED light (25mA 3.3V 7000mcd High intensity recommended).
  • One 1cm long small plastic tube (you can strip a 20-22 gauge wire for this).
  • One or two, CR2032 or CR2016 3V batteries.
  • Print one Shell.stl.
  • Print either the One Battery Cover.stl or the Two Battery Cover.stl depending on what battery configuration you are using.
    • All of the parts, except the plastic printed parts, should be easily found in your local Radio Shack (USA) or electronics store. There are as few choices to choose from. If you are using one CR2032 battery or two CR2016 batteries, print out the one battery cover button. If you are using two CR2032 batteries, you will need the two battery cover. The one battery cover is flush with the rest of the keychain, so it will look better, but two batteries will make your LED much brighter and more usefull. I've also included my blender file, should you want to change anything. I've left all of the raw subtractive models in it, so you could even swap the motorcycle for your own keychain design if you wanted to put a light on it. Assembly:
    First, you will want to decide which way to insert your batteries, this depends on which direction you install your LED. Once you have decided that, you will want to take your little plastic tube and put it on the top lead of your LED. This plastic tube prevents an electrical connection between the LED and the corner of the top most battery. If you don't use the plastic tube, chances are your LED will always be lit even without pressing the button. Now insert the LED in through the battery opening of the keychain and push it into place. It should be snug enough that the LED won't just fall out. Insert one or two batteries as explained above. Here, you may want to adjust the bend in the top LED lead so it is parallel with the top battery, but doesn't touch it. At this point, you should be able to push the top lead down until it touches the battery and the LED should light. Snap on the chosen cover, making sure that the top LED lead sits underneath where the button is going to be. Once the cover is snapped into place, the LED should not be lit by itself, but should light when you apply pressure to the button. There you go! Now show your friends and make them beg you to make them one too! The keychain shell also includes a very small, but handy, hole on the bottom. If you ever need to remove the batteries, you can push a pin or something through it to help you get them out.

description.text:
In Taiwan, 春 means spring and we hang couplets with the word around the house during the lunar new year.

Try to search google for the following formula:

x^4+y^4+100/(x^4+(2y-2)^4+(2y-1)^2)+100/(x^4+(2y+2)^4+(2y+1)^2)-1/((y+3)^4+(x/15)^4)-1/((y+4)^4+(x/15)^4)-1/((y+5)^4+(x/15)^4)-1/(4(x+y+4)^4+((x-y+1)/5)^4)-100^16/(((x-4)^2+(y+5)^2-13)^2+((x-19)^2+(y+12)^2-400)^2)^16-25

I found this amazing formula on "如何用方程式寫春聯" and tried to made an printable version. The function in OpenSCAD is: 

function f(x, y) = pow(x, 4) + pow(y, 4) + 100 / (pow(x, 4) + pow(2 * y - 2, 4) + pow(2 * y - 1, 2)) + 100 / (pow(x, 4) + pow(2 * y + 2, 4) + pow(2 * y + 1, 2)) - 1 / (pow(y + 3, 4) + pow(x / 15, 4)) - 1 / (pow(y + 4, 4) + pow(x / 15, 4)) - 1 / (pow(y + 5, 4) + pow(x / 15, 4)) - 1 / (4 * pow((x + y + 4), 4) + pow((x - y + 1) / 5, 4)) - pow(100, 16) / pow((pow(pow(x - 4, 2) + pow(y + 5, 2) - 13, 2) + pow(pow(x - 19, 2) + pow(y + 12, 2) - 400, 2)), 16) - 25;

title: 100mm extrusion calibration for FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
These are ready-to-use X3G files for the FlashForge Creator Pro and similar printers, to perform the calibration procedure as explained on the MatterHackers site. The files will instruct the printer to extrude exactly 100mm of filament. Ideally, this will result in exactly 100 mm of filament going into the extruder, but in practice this will usually be less, sometimes a bit more. To compensate for this during actual printing, an extrusion multiplier must be applied.
 

How to use

First, load the filament of which you want to measure the extrusion multiplier.
Instead of loading it from a spool through the guide tubes as usual, it is recommended cut off a strand of filament. Insert this directly into the extruder without the guide tube, such that the strand simply sticks out from the top of the extruder carriage (as shown in the photo). The length sticking out should be at least 100mm, preferably a bit more. If you want to repeat the test a few times (which is a good idea), you'll obviously need a longer strand.

Doing the test like this, has several advantages:

  1. It is much easier to measure and mark the length of filament sticking out from the extruder. You can simply use the distance to the end of the strand as your initial length. Still, if you want to make an explicit mark, either use a marker, a piece of tape, or a clip (I find muzz64's ‘Germz’ quite handy for this purpose).
  2. The result will not be influenced by the filament bending and twisting inside the guide tubes, which could introduce a large measurement error.
  3. You do not risk unwrapping and tangling the filament spool during the tests.

Next, measure and mark a known distance on the filament, starting from a reference point. This distance should be at least 100mm, preferably with some extra (e.g. 110mm). If you follow the above recommendations and use a strand of filament, your reference point should be the top of the extruder carriage, and your mark could simply be the end of the strand.

Next, pick the x3g file for the desired extruder and temperature, and ‘print’ it. Temperature is not crucial, you should pick a temperature that is high enough for the filament to flow but not too high to bake it.
When it has finished, measure the remaining distance between the reference point and your mark (or end of the strand). You can calculate the extrusion multiplier from the difference between the measured and expected distance (100 mm).

For instance, if you marked 110 mm and the final distance is 17 mm, you extruded 17 -
(110 - 100) = 7 mm less than expected, or only 93 mm instead of 100. This means your extrusion multiplier should be 100/93 = 1.0753.
Other example: you marked 120 mm and the final distance is 9 mm. You extruded (120 - 100) - 9 = 11 mm more than expected. This means your extrusion multiplier should be 100/111 = 0.9009.

The first example is more likely than the latter, because you will usually get under-extrusion due to the extruder gear teeth biting into the filament. See the bottom of this page for an explanation.
 

Remarks

You should repeat the test at least twice for the same filament to check consistency of the result. If the two tests deviate, do a third one to get a better estimate.
The test must be repeated for every different filament, although you can probably safely assume that different colors of the same material from the same brand will yield the same results.

The extrusion rate during the test should be slow enough for most filaments. If you find it extrudes too fast for some really flexible filament or so, either modify the source files and convert them to X3G files using GPX, or ask me.

Mind that it is not essential to get the extrusion multiplier correct to umpteen digits after the decimal point. In fact, from this test I found out that I had been under-extruding for a long time, yet my prints were accurate and reliable. In the end, use the multiplier that provides the best results in practice, not in theory.

This method will only compensate for the difference in expected versus actual extruded length. It does not compensate for incorrect filament diameter, and the extrusion multiplier is not meant for that in the first place. You should always measure the exact diameter of your filament and configure it in your slicing software.

description.header: Why is the extrusion multiplier needed?
description.text:
Most extruder designs rely on a geared wheel that pushes against another spring-loaded wheel. The teeth of the gear provide a good grip on the filament clamped in between the two wheels. However, the softer the material, the deeper the teeth will dig into the filament, and the smaller the effective radius of the driving gear becomes. To extrude a certain length of filament, a gear with a smaller effective radius will need to make more turns than one with a larger radius.

Your printer's firmware is configured with some reasonable default conversion factor between extrusion coordinates in print commands, and the number of motor steps required to pull the instructed length of filament through the extruder. This default was chosen for some typical filament, and will not be correct for a softer or harder filament. This is where the extrusion multiplier is needed.

Some firmwares allow to send a command with the multiplier, which is then automatically applied to all coordinates. Sailfish (as used by the FFCP) however, does not allow this, therefore the extrusion coordinates themselves must already be multiplied before sending them to the printer.

Sailfish executes the raw X3G files which directly contain the number of steps. This means the extrusion multiplier must already have been taken into consideration while writing the .x3g. Even if you would find some way to apply a global multiplier between what is in the x3g files and what the printer actually extrudes, it would be a bad idea because you would need to manually change this every time you swap filaments.
You must configure the extrusion multiplier in your slicing program. Every program should allow to make a profile per filament, and enter the multiplier per filament. Again, you shouldn't try to make a global calibration for the entire printer because that doesn't make sense.
comments.author: aceycv8

comments.text: "there is no standard way to specify the multiplier to be used during gcode-to-x3g conversion. "
comments.author: DrLex

comments.text:
Slic3r only outputs gcode files. To obtain an X3G file, it must be separately converted with for instance the GPX program (which of course can be configured to be an automated post-processing step). GPX is usually invoked with a machine preset that determines the steps per mm. It would indeed be better if the G-code file would simply contain the ideal E coordinates for perfect filament, plus a separate extrusion multiplier that depends on the actual filament diameter and squishiness. This would allow to convert the same gcode file into an X3G with a different multiplier, without having to re-slice it.
Slic3r does allow to output gcode with so-called ‘volumetric E’ coordinates, which specify only the volume of filament needed per print move (not even the length, so it is independent of filament diameter). An extra G-code command at the start of the file sets the conversion factor between those E coordinates and the actual extruded lengths. Some firmwares support this, like the most recent Marlin versions if I have to believe the documentation.

title: Monoprice Ultimate Bladeless Cooling Duct
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
It's finally here! This part took a lot of planning and considerations, don't let its simple look fool you.

So what is it? It replaces the cooling fan shroud on the Monoprice Maker Ultimate or Wanhao D6 printers. The shroud is a bladeless fan style, which uses 'inducement' and 'entrainment' to create a column of airflow that not only blows air, but also draws in surrounding air to create a consistent flow of air through the whole inner area of the ring. If you'd like to know more how this functions, just look up how bladeless fans work!

So what makes this part so special? Well for starters, it doesn't require any supports or special print settings! It's a simplified and efficient design. Not as stylish as I would like, but sometimes function supersedes form. Secondly, it has a large profile, which keeps it away from the hot end, so no issues with drooping. It isn't soo large that it interferes with anything though, so your full print area is still there, no hotend wires pushing on it, nothing! It's also relatively thin, but supported well. The combination of distance and material efficiency, together create a lower thermal mass part, so when air flows through, it's not heating up as much as it otherwise would and is actually cooling down, which means cooler air on your filament!

Print with the air exhaust port located on the ring, facing down. Part will reduce print area slightly in the back of the bed, so make sure to reduce your bed area appropriately in your slicer.

Testimony: After printing with this thing, I can safely say with certainty that it performs noticeably better than JGTMaker's fan duct! I've uploaded some pictures to prove it. I printed my HTC Vive controller holders using the same gcode file, one with my duct and one with JGTMaker's version.

The controller holder models are printed at a straight 45 degree angle, so the model is largely an unsupported steep overhang, which makes cooling a critical need so the layers don't droop on the overhang. The imperfections are virtually the same across both prints due to them using the same sliced gcode file, but there are key differences.

Firstly, you can see defects are noticeably less raised/pronounced from the surface, indicating better layer cohesion from cooling. On top of that there is no warping, while with JGTMaker's you can see some warping in the lower wall, which is much more pronounced when viewed from a side profile and creates a noticeable dip in the prints surface. That dip would be a pain to sand out. There is no dip on my duct. There are other little differences here and there, but overall the quality difference is noticeable.

I'd like to also note that with the stock duct, this item would print terribly, with tons of blobbing and non cohesive layers below the 45 degree overhang, so I know that both ducts are indeed performing the job they were meant to do.

You could say that print or environment settings could mitigate some of these quality issues, but the whole point is to make a direct comparison, and the comparison shows that my duct comes out on top under the same conditions.
